div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1816">We must think about the tangent lines to the graph of \(f\=
text{,}\) because the slopes of these lines are the values of \(f'(x)\text{=
.}\)</p>
<p id=3D"p-1817">We start by checking the graph of \(f\) for horizontal tan=
gent lines, since horizontal lines have a slope of 0. We find that the tang=
ent line is horizontal at the points where \(x\) has the values -1.9 and 1.=
8 (approximately). At each of these values of \(x\text{,}\) we must have \(=
f'(x)=3D0\text{,}\) which means that the graph of \(f'\) has an \(x\)-inter=
cept (a point where the graph intersects the \(x\)-axis).</p>
<p id=3D"p-1818">Note that horizontal tangent lines have a slope of zero an=
d these occur approximately at the points \((-1.9,-3.2)\) and \((1.8,3.2)\)=
 of the graph. Therefore \(f'(x)\) will cross the \(x\)-axis when \(x=3D-1.=
9\) and \(x=3D1.8\text{.}\)</p>
<p id=3D"p-1819">Analyzing the slope of the tangent line of \(f(x)\) at \(x=
=3D0\) gives approximately \(3.0\text{,}\) thus, \(f'(0)=3D3.0\text{.}\) Si=
milarly, analyzing the slope of the tangent lines of \(f(x)\) at \(x=3D1\) =
and \(x=3D-1\) give approximately \(2.0\) for both, thus, \(f'(1)=3Df'(-1)=
=3D2.0\text{.}\)</p>
