div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1822">By the definition of derivative (using \(h\) in place of \=
(\Delta x\)) we have,</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split} f'(x)\amp =3D\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}=3D\lim_{h\to =
0}\frac{(m(x+h)+b)-(mx+b)}{h}\\ \amp =3D\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{mh}{h}=3D\lim_{h=
\to 0}m=3Dm. \end{split}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1823">This is not surprising. We know that \(f'(x)\) always repr=
esents the slope of a tangent line to the graph of \(f\text{.}\) In this ex=
ample, since the graph of \(f\) is a straight line \(y=3Dmx+b\) already, ev=
ery tangent line is the same line \(y=3Dmx+b\text{.}\) Since this line has =
a slope of \(m\text{,}\) we must have \(f'(x)=3Dm\text{.}\)</p>
</div></div>
