div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1830">If \(x\) is positive, then this is the function \(y=3Dx\te=
xt{,}\) whose derivative is the constant 1. (Recall that when \(y=3Df(x)=3D=
mx+b\text{,}\) the derivative is the slope \(m\text{.}\)) If \(x\) is negat=
ive, then we're dealing with the function \(y=3D-x\text{,}\) whose derivati=
ve is the constant \(-1\text{.}\) If \(x=3D0\text{,}\) then the function ha=
s a corner, i.e., there is no tangent line. A tangent line would have to po=
int in the direction of the curve=E2=80=94but there are <em class=3D"emphas=
is">two</em> directions of the curve that come together at the origin.</p>
<p id=3D"p-1831"></p><div class=3D"image-box" style=3D"width: 46%; margin-l=
eft: 27%; margin-right: 27%;"><img src=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenot=
es/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/images/absvalue.svg" style=3D"width: 100%; h=
eight: auto;" alt=3D""></div><p id=3D"p-1831-part2"></p>
<p id=3D"p-1832">We can summarize this as</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
y'=3D\left\{\begin{array}{rl} 1, \amp  \mbox{if \(x&gt;0\),} \\ -1, \amp  \=
mbox{if \(x\lt 0\),} \\ \hbox{undefined,} \amp  \mbox{if \(x=3D0\).} \end{a=
rray} \right.
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1833">In particular, the absolute value function \(f(x)=3D|x|\) =
is <em class=3D"emphasis">not</em> differentiable at \(x=3D0\text{.}\)</p>
</div></div>
</div></article><p id=3D"p-1834"><div class=3D"autopermalink"><a href=3D"ht=
