proof-5" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><article class=3D"hiddenpr=
oof"><p id=3D"p-1836">Suppose that \(f\) is differentiable at \(a\text{.}\)=
 That is,</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
f^{\prime }\left( a\right) =3D\lim_{h\rightarrow 0}\frac{f\left( a+h\right)=
 -f\left( a\right) }{h}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1836-part2">exists. At this stage, we find it convenient to writ=
e this limit in an alternative form so that its connection with continuity =
can become more easily seen. If we let \(x=3Da+h\text{,}\) then \(h=3Dx-a\t=
ext{.}\) Furthermore, \(h\rightarrow 0\) is equivalent to \(x\rightarrow a\=
text{.}\) So,</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
f^{\prime }\left( a\right) =3D\lim_{x\rightarrow a}\frac{f\left( x\right) -=
f\left( a\right) }{x-a}\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1837">(This alternative formulation of the derivative is also st=
andard. We will use it whenever we find it convenient to do so. You should =
get familiar with it.) Continuity at \(a\) can now be proved as follows:</p=
>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split}
\lim_{x\rightarrow a}f\left( x\right) \amp =3D \lim_{x\rightarrow a}\left( =
\frac{ f\left( x\right) -f\left( a\right) }{x-a}\cdot \left( x-a\right) +f\=
left( a\right) \right)\\
=3D\amp \lim_{x\rightarrow a}\frac{f\left( x\right) -f\left( a\right) }{x-a=
}\cdot \lim_{x\rightarrow a}\left( x-a\right) +\lim_{x\rightarrow a}f\left(=
 a\right)\\
=3D\amp f^{\prime }\left( a\right) \cdot \left( a-a\right) +f\left( a\right=
)\\
=3D\amp f\left( a\right)
\end{split}
\end{equation*}
</div></article></div>
