<p id=3D"p-1851">To find \(f'(x)\text{,}\) we compute</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split} f(x+h) - f(x) \amp =3D (x+h)^{2} - 4(x+h) \\[1ex] \amp =3D x^=
{2} + 2xh + h^{2} - 4x -4h - (x^{2} - 4x)\\[1ex] \amp =3D 2xh + h^{2} - 4h =
\\[1ex] \amp =3D h\left(2x + h -4 \right) \\[1ex] \dfrac{f(x+h) - f(x)}{h} =
\amp =3D 2x +h - 4 \end{split}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1851-part2">Therefore,</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
f'(x) =3D \lim\limits_{h \to 0} \dfrac{f(x+h) - f(x)}{h} =3D \lim\limits_{h=
 \to 0}  \left(2x +h - 4\right) =3D 2x - 4\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-562"><p id=3D"p-1852">At a point on the graph of \(f\) where t=
he tangent line to the curve is horizontal and hence has zero slope, the de=
rivative \(f'\) of \(f\) is zero. Accordingly, to find such points, we set =
\(f'(x) =3D 0\text{,}\) which gives \(2x-4 =3D 0\text{,}\) or \(x =3D 2\tex=
t{.}\) The corresponding value of \(y\) is given by \(y =3D f(2) =3D -4\tex=
t{,}\) and so the desired point is \(\left(2,-4\right)\text{.}\)</p></li>
<li id=3D"li-563"><p id=3D"p-1853">The graph of \(f\) and the tangent line =
