%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-241" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1899">By the definition of velocity and acceleration we need to =
compute \(f'(t)\) and \(f''(t)\text{.}\) Using the definition of derivative=
, we have,</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
f'(t)=3D\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{(t+h)^2-t^2}{h}=3D\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{2th+h^2}{h}=
=3D\lim_{h\to 0}(2t+h)=3D2t\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1900">Therefore, \(v(t)=3Df'(t)=3D2t\text{.}\) Thus, the velocit=
y at time \(t=3D1\) is \(v(1)=3D2~m/s\text{.}\) We now have that the accele=
ration at time \(t\) is:</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
a(t)=3Df''(t)=3D\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{2(t+h)-2t}{h}=3D\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{2h}{h=
}=3D2\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1901">Therefore, \(a(t)=3D2\text{.}\) Substituting \(t=3D1\) int=
o the function \(a(t)\) gives \(a(1)=3D2~m/s^2\text{.}\)</p>
</div></div>
