%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-249" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1918">First, we notice that the slope of \(f\) is symmetric abou=
t the line \(x=3D2\text{.}\) This means that the function \(f'(x)\) will be=
 symmetric about \(x=3D2\text{.}\) We next indicate on the graph of \(f\) t=
he points at which \(f'(x) =3D 0\text{,}\) and add these points to our grap=
h of \(f'(x)\text{:}\)</p>
<div class=3D"sidebyside"><div class=3D"sbsrow" style=3D"margin-left:0%;mar=
gin-right:0%;">
<div class=3D"sbspanel" style=3D"width:50%;justify-content:flex-start;"><im=
g src=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/im=
ages/image-215.svg" style=3D"width: 100%; height: auto;" alt=3D""></div>
<div class=3D"sbspanel" style=3D"width:50%;justify-content:flex-start;"><im=
g src=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/im=
ages/image-216.svg" style=3D"width: 100%; height: auto;" alt=3D""></div>
</div></div>
<p id=3D"p-1919">Next, we estimate the slope of the tangent line to \(f\) a=
t the points \(x=3D0.5\) and \(x=3D1.5\) using the points \((0,2)\) and \((=
1,3)\) and \((2,2)\text{.}\) As shown the graph below to the left, the slop=
e of these lines are good approximations to the slopes of the desired tange=
nt lines. Therefore,</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
f'(0.5) \approx \frac{2-3}{0-1} =3D 1, \text{ and }  f'(1.5) \approx \frac{=
3-2}{1-2} =3D -1\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1920">We add the points \((0.5,1)\) and \((1.5,-1)\) to our grap=
h of \(f'(x)\) and then reflect across our axis of symmetry:</p>
<div class=3D"sidebyside"><div class=3D"sbsrow" style=3D"margin-left:0%;mar=
gin-right:0%;">
<div class=3D"sbspanel" style=3D"width:50%;justify-content:flex-start;"><im=
g src=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/im=
ages/image-217.svg" style=3D"width: 100%; height: auto;" alt=3D""></div>
<div class=3D"sbspanel" style=3D"width:50%;justify-content:flex-start;"><im=
g src=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/im=
ages/image-218.svg" style=3D"width: 100%; height: auto;" alt=3D""></div>
</div></div>
<p id=3D"p-1921">We can connect the points smoothly to obtain a rough graph=
 of \(f'(x)\text{.}\) The exact result is shown below.</p>
<div class=3D"image-box" style=3D"width: 60%; margin-left: 20%; margin-righ=
