<span class=3D"type">Exercise</span> <span class=3D"codenumber">4.2.3</span=
>.</h6></a></article><div id=3D"hk-exercise-160" class=3D"hidden-content te=
x2jax_ignore"><article class=3D"exercise-like"><p id=3D"p-1922">Shown is th=
e graph of a function \(f(x)\text{.}\) Sketch the graph of \(f'(x)\) by est=
imating the derivative at a number of points in the interval: estimate the =
derivative at regular intervals from one end of the interval to the other, =
and also at =E2=80=9Cspecial=E2=80=9D points, as when the derivative is zer=
o. Make sure you indicate any places where the derivative does not exist. <=
/p><div class=3D"image-box" style=3D"width: 60%; margin-left: 20%; margin-r=
ight: 20%;"><img src=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Co=
urse%20Notes/images/image-220.svg" style=3D"width: 100%; height: auto;" alt=
=3D""></div><p id=3D"p-1922-part2"></p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-250" id=3D"so=
lution-250" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-250" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1923">First, we consider the derivative \(f'(x)\) on the interva=
l \(\left(0,2\right)\text{.}\) Here, \(f(x)\) is a line, and so the slope o=
f the tangent line to \(f\) is constant, and therefore its derivative is co=
nstant (and equal to the slope of the line, here \(1\)).</p>
<p id=3D"p-1924">At \(x =3D 2\text{,}\) there is a corner, thus the derivat=
ive does not exist.</p>
<p id=3D"p-1925">On the interval \(\left(2,3\right)\text{,}\) the slope of =
the tangent lines are negative, and so \(f'(x)\) will take on negative valu=
es. Now, look at the slope of the tangent line between, say , \(x_{1}=3D2.1=
\) and \(x_{2}=3D2.2\text{.}\) The slope is steeper (more negative) at \(x_=
{1}=3D2.1\text{,}\) by an amount that appears proportional to \(\Delta x =
=3D 0.1\) =E2=80=94 we verify with a careful drawing that \(\dfrac{m_{1}-m_=
{2}}{\Delta x} =3D 2\text{.}\) This behaviour is the same on the entire int=
erval, and so we see that, here, \(f'(x)\) is an increasing line with slope=
 \(2\) which takes on negative values.</p>
<p id=3D"p-1926">At \(x=3D3\text{,}\) the tangent line is horizontal and so=
 \(f'(x)=3D0\text{.}\)</p>
<p id=3D"p-1927">Finally, on the interval \(\left(3,\infty\right)\text{,}\)=
 we notice that the tangent lines have positive slope, but otherwise exhibi=
t the same behaviour as on the interval \(\left(2,3\right)\text{.}\) Puttin=
g this all together, we get the following sketch for \(f'(x)\text{:}\)</p>
<div class=3D"image-box" style=3D"width: 60%; margin-left: 20%; margin-righ=
t: 20%;"><img src=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Cours=
e%20Notes/images/image-221.svg" style=3D"width: 100%; height: auto;" alt=3D=
""></div>
</div></div></article></div>
<article class=3D"exercise-like" id=3D"exercise-161"><a data-knowl=3D"" cla=
ss=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-exercise-161" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/mat=
h-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><=
h6 class=3D"heading">
<span class=3D"type">Exercise</span> <span class=3D"codenumber">4.2.4</span=
>.</h6></a></article><div id=3D"hk-exercise-161" class=3D"hidden-content te=
x2jax_ignore"><article class=3D"exercise-like"><p id=3D"p-1928">Find an equ=
ation for the tangent line to the graph of \(\ds f(x)=3D5-x-3x^2\) at the p=
oint \(x=3D2\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-317" id=3D"answ=
er-317" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-317" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(y=3D-13x+17\)</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-251" id=3D"so=
lution-251" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-251" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1929">We first find the point of tangency:</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
(2,f(2)) =3D (2, 5-2-3(4)) =3D (2,-9)
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1930">Next, we calculate the derivative of \(f\) using the defin=
ition of the derivative:</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split} f'(x) \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}\\ \amp =3D=
 \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{(5-(x+h)-3(x+h)^2) - (5-x-3x^2)}{h} \\ \amp =3D \lim_=
{h\to 0} \frac{5 - x - h - 3(x^2+2xh+h^2) - 5 + x +3x^2}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim=
_{h\to 0} \frac{-h-6xh-3h^2}{h} \\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{-h(1+6x+3h)=
}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} -(1+6x+3h)\\ \amp =3D -(1+6x) \end{split}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1931">Therefore, the slope of the tangent line is</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
f'(2) =3D -(1+6(2)) =3D -13\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1932">All together, the equation of the tangent line (in point-s=
lope form) is</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
y + 9 =3D -13(x-2)\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
</div></div></article></div>
<article class=3D"exercise-like" id=3D"exercise-162"><a data-knowl=3D"" cla=
ss=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-exercise-162" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/mat=
h-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><=
h6 class=3D"heading">
<span class=3D"type">Exercise</span> <span class=3D"codenumber">4.2.5</span=
>.</h6></a></article><div id=3D"hk-exercise-162" class=3D"hidden-content te=
x2jax_ignore"><article class=3D"exercise-like"><p id=3D"p-1933">Find a valu=
e for \(a\) so that the graph of \(\ds f(x)=3Dx^2+ax-3\) has a horizontal t=
angent line at \(x=3D4\text{.}\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-318" id=3D"answ=
er-318" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-318" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(-8\)</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-252" id=3D"so=
lution-252" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-252" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1934">We wish to find a value of \(a\) for which the function \(=
f(x)=3Dx^{2}+ax-4\) has a horizontal tangent line at \(x=3D4\text{.}\) We f=
irst compute \(f'(x)\text{:}\)</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split} f'(x) \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} \\ \amp =
=3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{((x+h)^2+a(x+h)-4)-(x^2+ax-4)}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{=
h\to 0} \frac{(x^2+2xh+h^2+ax+ah-4)-(x^2+ax-4)}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0}=
 \frac{2xh+h^2+ah}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \left(2x+h+a\right) =3D 2x+a=
 \end{split}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1935">Therefore, \(f'(4)=3D 8+a\text{.}\) The function \(f\) wil=
l have a horizontal tangent line here if \(f'(4)=3D0 \implies a=3D-8\text{.=
}\) We verify with a sketch:</p>
<div class=3D"image-box" style=3D"width: 60%; margin-left: 20%; margin-righ=
t: 20%;"><img src=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Cours=
e%20Notes/images/image-222.svg" style=3D"width: 100%; height: auto;" alt=3D=
""></div>
</div></div></article></div>
<article class=3D"exercise-like" id=3D"exercise-163"><a data-knowl=3D"" cla=
ss=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-exercise-163" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/mat=
h-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><=
h6 class=3D"heading">
<span class=3D"type">Exercise</span> <span class=3D"codenumber">4.2.6</span=
>.</h6></a></article><div id=3D"hk-exercise-163" class=3D"hidden-content te=
x2jax_ignore"><article class=3D"exercise-like"><p id=3D"p-1936">Find the sl=
ope of the tangent line to the graph of the given function at any point.</p=
>
<ol class=3D"lower-alpha">
<li id=3D"li-600">
<p id=3D"p-1937">\(f(x)=3D7\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-319" id=3D"answ=
er-319" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-319" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(0\)</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-253" id=3D"so=
lution-253" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-253" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution"><p id=3D"p-1938">Since \(f(x)\) is a constant functi=
on, the slope of the tangent line will be zero for all \(x\text{.}\)</p></d=
iv></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-601">
<p id=3D"p-1939">\(f(x)=3Dx+5\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-320" id=3D"answ=
er-320" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-320" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(1\)</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-254" id=3D"so=
lution-254" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-254" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution"><p id=3D"p-1940">The function \(f(x) =3D x+5\) is a =
line, and therefore has a constant slope, \(m=3D1\text{.}\) Thus, for all \=
(x\text{,}\) the slope of the tangent line will be 1.</p></div></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-602">
<p id=3D"p-1941">\(f(x)=3D2x^{2}\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-321" id=3D"answ=
er-321" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-321" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(4x\)</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-255" id=3D"so=
lution-255" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-255" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1942">The function \(f(x)=3D2x^2\) is a parabola, and so has a n=
on-constant slope. Therefore, we compute the derivative:</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split} f'(x) \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} \\ \amp =
=3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{2(x+h)^2 - 2x^2}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{=
2(x^2+2xh+h^2) - 2x^2}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{2x^2 + 4xh + 2h^2 =
- 2x^2}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{h(4x+2h)}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\t=
o 0} (4x+2h)\\ \amp =3D 4x \end{split}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1942-part2">Therefore, at any point \(x=3Da\) is \(4a\text{.}\)<=
/p>
</div></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-603">
<p id=3D"p-1943">\(f(x)=3D\sqrt{3x-1}\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-322" id=3D"answ=
er-322" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-322" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(\dfrac{3}{2\sqrt{3x-1}}\)</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-256" id=3D"so=
lution-256" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-256" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1944">The square root function has a non-constant slope, and so =
we need to compute \(f'(x)\text{:}\)</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split} f'(x) \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} \\ \amp =
=3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{\sqrt{3(x+h)-1}-\sqrt{3x-1}}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\=
to 0} \frac{\sqrt{3(x+h)-1}-\sqrt{3x-1}}{h} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{3(x+h)-1}+\sq=
rt{3x-1}}{\sqrt{3(x+h)-1}+\sqrt{3x-1}}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{3h}{h=
\sqrt{3(x+h)-1}+\sqrt{3x-1}}\\ \amp =3D  \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{3}{\sqrt{3(x+h=
)-1}+\sqrt{3x-1}}\\ \amp =3D \frac{3}{2\sqrt{3x-1}} \end{split}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1944-part2">Hence, the slope of the tangent line at any point \(=
x=3Da\) is given by \(\dfrac{3}{2\sqrt{3a-1}}\text{.}\)</p>
</div></div>
</li>
</ol></article></div>
<article class=3D"exercise-like" id=3D"exercise-164"><a data-knowl=3D"" cla=
ss=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-exercise-164" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/mat=
h-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><=
h6 class=3D"heading">
<span class=3D"type">Exercise</span> <span class=3D"codenumber">4.2.7</span=
>.</h6></a></article><div id=3D"hk-exercise-164" class=3D"hidden-content te=
x2jax_ignore"><article class=3D"exercise-like"><p id=3D"p-1945">Find the sl=
ope of the tangent line to the graph of each function at the given point an=
d determine an equation of the tangent line.</p>
<ol class=3D"lower-alpha">
<li id=3D"li-604">
<p id=3D"p-1946">\(f(x)=3D2x+7\) at \((1,1)\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-323" id=3D"answ=
er-323" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-323" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(2\text{;}\) \(y=3D2x-1\)</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-257" id=3D"so=
lution-257" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-257" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1947">We first compute the derivative of \(f(x)\) for any \(x\) =
using the definition of the derivative:</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split} f'(x) \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} \\ \amp =
=3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{(2(x+h)+7) - (2x+7)}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \f=
rac{2x+2h+7 - 2x - 7}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{2h}{h} \\ \amp =3D =
2 \end{split}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1947-part2">Therefore, at the point \((1,1)\) the slope of the t=
angent line is 2. The equation of the tangent line is thus</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
y - 1 =3D 2(x-1)\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
</div></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-605">
<p id=3D"p-1948">\(f(x)=3D-\dfrac{1}{x}\) at \((2,-1)\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-324" id=3D"answ=
er-324" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-324" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(\frac{1}{4}\text{;}\) \(y=3D\frac{1}{4}x-\frac{3}{2}\)</di=
v></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-258" id=3D"so=
lution-258" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-258" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1949">The derivative of \(f(x)\) is found to be:</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split} f'(x) \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} \\ \amp =
=3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{\frac{-1}{x+h} - \frac{-1}{x}}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{=
h\to 0} \frac{\frac{-x+(x+h)}{x(x+h)}}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{\f=
rac{h}{x(x+h)}}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{1}{x(x+h)}\\ \amp =3D \fr=
ac{1}{x^2} \end{split}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1949-part2">Hence, at the point \((2,-1)\) the slope of the tang=
ent line is \(\dfrac{1}{(2)^2} =3D \dfrac{1}{4}\text{.}\) Therefore, the eq=
uation of the tangent line is</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
y + 1 =3D \frac{1}{4} (x-2)\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
</div></div>
</li>
</ol></article></div>
<article class=3D"exercise-like" id=3D"exercise-165"><a data-knowl=3D"" cla=
ss=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-exercise-165" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/mat=
h-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><=
h6 class=3D"heading">
<span class=3D"type">Exercise</span> <span class=3D"codenumber">4.2.8</span=
>.</h6></a></article><div id=3D"hk-exercise-165" class=3D"hidden-content te=
x2jax_ignore"><article class=3D"exercise-like"><p id=3D"p-1950">Let \(f(x) =
=3D x^{2}-2x+1\text{.}\)</p>
<ol class=3D"lower-alpha">
<li id=3D"li-606">
<p id=3D"p-1951">Determine the derivative \(f'\) of \(f\text{.}\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-325" id=3D"answ=
er-325" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-325" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(f'(x)=3D2x-2\)</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-259" id=3D"so=
lution-259" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-259" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1952">Using the definition of the derivative, we compute \(f'(x)=
\text{:}\)</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split} f'(x) \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{\frac{h}{x(x+h)}}{h}\\ \am=
p =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{\left((x+h)^2-2(x+h)+1\right)-\left(x^2-2x+1\righ=
t)}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{\left(x^2+2xh+h^2 - 2x-2h +1\right) -=
\left(x^2-2x+1\right)}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{2xh+h^2-2h}{h}\\ \=
amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{h(2x+h-2)}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} (2x+h-2)=
\\ \amp =3D 2x -2 \end{split}
\end{equation*}
</div>
</div></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-607">
<p id=3D"p-1953">Determine the point on the graph of \(f\) where the tangen=
t line to the curve is horizontal.</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-326" id=3D"answ=
er-326" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-326" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\((1,0)\)</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-260" id=3D"so=
lution-260" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-260" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1954">The tangent line to \(f\) is horizontal when \(f'(x)=3D0\t=
ext{.}\) Therefore, we set</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split} f'(x) \amp =3D 0 \\ 2x -2 \amp =3D 0\\ x \amp =3D 1. \end{spl=
it}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1954-part2">Therefore, the tangent line is horizontal at the poi=
nt</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\left(1,f(1)\right) =3D \left(1, 1-2+1\right) =3D \left(1,0\right)\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
</div></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-608">
<p id=3D"p-1955">Sketch the graph of \(f\) and the tangent line to the curv=
e at the point found in part (b).</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-327" id=3D"answ=
er-327" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-327" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution"><div class=3D"image-box" style=3D"width: 60%; margin-left: 2=
0%; margin-right: 20%;"><img src=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Mat=
h%20157%20Course%20Notes/images/image-223.svg" style=3D"width: 100%; height=
: auto;" alt=3D""></div></div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-261" id=3D"so=
lution-261" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-261" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1956">Notice that the function</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
f(x) =3D x^2-2x+1
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1956-part2">is a parabola (opening upwards) with vertex \((1,0)\=
text{,}\) which is the point identified above. We make the following sketch=
: </p><div class=3D"image-box" style=3D"width: 60%; margin-left: 20%; margi=
n-right: 20%;"><img src=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%2=
0Course%20Notes/images/image-224.svg" style=3D"width: 100%; height: auto;" =
alt=3D""></div><p id=3D"p-1956-part3"></p>
</div></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-609">
<p id=3D"p-1957">Determine the rate of change of \(f\) at the point found i=
n part(b).</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-328" id=3D"answ=
er-328" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-328" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(0\)</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-262" id=3D"so=
lution-262" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-262" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution"><p id=3D"p-1958">From our work above, we determine t=
hat the rate of change at \(x=3D1\) is zero.</p></div></div>
</li>
</ol></article></div>
<article class=3D"exercise-like" id=3D"exercise-166"><a data-knowl=3D"" cla=
ss=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-exercise-166" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/mat=
h-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><=
h6 class=3D"heading">
<span class=3D"type">Exercise</span> <span class=3D"codenumber">4.2.9</span=
>.</h6></a></article><div id=3D"hk-exercise-166" class=3D"hidden-content te=
x2jax_ignore"><article class=3D"exercise-like"><p id=3D"p-1959">Let \(y=3Dh=
(t)=3Dt^{2}+t\text{.}\)</p>
<ol class=3D"lower-alpha">
<li id=3D"li-610">
<p id=3D"p-1960">Find the average rate of change of \(y\) with respect to \=
(t\) in the interval from \(t=3D2\) to \(t=3D3\text{,}\) from \(t=3D2\) to =
\(t=3D2.5\text{,}\) and from \(t=3D2\) to \(t=3D2.1\text{.}\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-329" id=3D"answ=
er-329" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-329" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(6\text{;}\)\(5.5\text{;}\)\(5.1\)</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-263" id=3D"so=
lution-263" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-263" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1961">The average rate of change of the function \(y=3Dh(t) =3D =
t^2+t\) from \(t=3D2\) to \(t=3D2+\Delta t\) is given by</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split} \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta t} \amp =3D \frac{(2+\Delta t)^2 + (2+=
 \Delta t) - (2^2+2)}{\Delta t} \\ \amp =3D \frac{4+4\Delta t + \Delta t^2 =
+ 2 + \Delta t - 4 - 2}{\Delta t}\\ \amp =3D \frac{4\Delta t + \Delta t^2 +=
 \Delta t}{\Delta t}\\ \amp =3D 5 + \Delta t \end{split}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1961-part2">Therefore, between \(t=3D2\) and \(t=3D3\) (\(\Delta=
 t=3D1\)), the average rate of change must be \(5 + 1 =3D 6\text{.}\) Betwe=
en \(t=3D2\) and \(t=3D2.5\) (\(\Delta t=3D0.5\)), the average rate of chan=
ge is \(5 + 0.25 =3D 5.25\text{.}\) Between \(t=3D2\) and \(t=3D2.1\) (\(\D=
elta t =3D0.1\)), the average rate of change is \(5+0.1 =3D 5.1\text{.}\)</=
p>
</div></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-611">
<p id=3D"p-1962">Find the (instantaneous) rate of change of \(y\) at \(t=3D=
2\text{.}\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-330" id=3D"answ=
er-330" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-330" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(5\)</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-264" id=3D"so=
lution-264" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-264" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1963">The instantaneous rate of change at \(t=3D2\) is therefore=
</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\lim_{\Delta t \to 0} 5 + \Delta t =3D 5\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
</div></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-612">
<p id=3D"p-1964">Compare the results obtained in part (a) with that of part=
 (b).</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-331" id=3D"answ=
er-331" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-331" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution"><p id=3D"p-1965"></p><p id=3D"p-1966">We notice that as we r=
efine \(\Delta t\) in part (b), our answers get closer and closer to our an=
swer in part (c), as expected.</p><p id=3D"p-1966-part2"></p></div></div>
</li>
</ol></article></div>
<article class=3D"exercise-like" id=3D"exercise-167"><a data-knowl=3D"" cla=
ss=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-exercise-167" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/mat=
h-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><=
h6 class=3D"heading">
<span class=3D"type">Exercise</span> <span class=3D"codenumber">4.2.10</spa=
n>.</h6></a></article><div id=3D"hk-exercise-167" class=3D"hidden-content t=
ex2jax_ignore"><article class=3D"exercise-like"><p id=3D"p-1967">The total =
cost \(C(q)\) (in dollars) incurred by a certain manufacturer in producing =
\(q\) units a day is given by</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
C(q)=3D-10q^{2}+300q+130 \ \ \ (0\leq q \leq 15)
\end{equation*}
</div>
<ol class=3D"lower-alpha">
<li id=3D"li-613">
<p id=3D"p-1968">Find \(C'(q)\text{.}\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-332" id=3D"answ=
er-332" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-332" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(C'(q)=3D-20q+300\)</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-265" id=3D"so=
lution-265" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-265" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1969">We differentiate with respect to \(q\text{:}\)</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split} C'(q) \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{C(q+h)-C(q)}{h}\\ \amp =3D=
 \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{\left(-10(q+h)^2+300(q+h)+130\right) - \left(-10q^2+30=
0q+130\right)}{h}\\ \amp =3D\lim_{h\to 0} \frac{-10(q^2+2qh+h^2) + 300q + 3=
00h + 130 + 10q^2 - 300q - 130}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{ -200qh -=
200h^2 + 300h}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{h(-200q-200h+300)}{h}\\ \a=
mp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \left(-200q- 200h + 300\right)\\ \amp =3D -200q+300 \e=
nd{split}
\end{equation*}
</div>
</div></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-614">
<p id=3D"p-1970">What is the rate of change of the total cost when the leve=
l of production is ten units?</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-333" id=3D"answ=
er-333" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-333" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">$\(100\) per unit</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-266" id=3D"so=
lution-266" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-266" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1971">If production level is set to 10 units, then the rate of c=
hange of the cost is</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
C'(10) =3D -200(1) + 300 =3D 100\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1971-part2">This means that the cost is increasing at a rate of =
$100.</p>
</div></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-615">
<p id=3D"p-1972">What is the average cost the manufacturer incurs when the =
level of production is ten units?</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-334" id=3D"answ=
er-334" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-334" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">$\(213\) per unit</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-267" id=3D"so=
lution-267" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-267" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1973">The average cost when \(q=3D10\) is</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\overline{C} =3D \frac{C(10)}{10} =3D \frac{-10(100)+300(10)+130}{10} =3D -=
100+300+13 =3D 213\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1973-part2">Therefore, when the production level is set to 10 un=
its, the average cost incurred is $213 per unit.</p>
</div></div>
</li>
</ol></article></div>
<article class=3D"exercise-like" id=3D"exercise-168"><a data-knowl=3D"" cla=
ss=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-exercise-168" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/mat=
h-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><=
h6 class=3D"heading">
<span class=3D"type">Exercise</span> <span class=3D"codenumber">4.2.11</spa=
n>.</h6></a></article><div id=3D"hk-exercise-168" class=3D"hidden-content t=
ex2jax_ignore"><article class=3D"exercise-like"><p id=3D"p-1974">A certain =
manufacturer produces beach umbrellas with a daily cost \(C(q)\) of</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
C(q)=3D0.000002q^{3}+5q+400\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1975">Calculate</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\dfrac{C(100+h)-C(100)}{h}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1975-part2">for \(h=3D1,0.1,0.001\text{,}\) and \(0.0001\text{.}=
\) Use your results to estimate the rate of change of the total cost functi=
on when the level of production is \(100\) units/day.</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-335" id=3D"answ=
er-335" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-335" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">$\(5.06060\text{,}\) $\(5.06006\text{,}\)$\(5.060006\text{,}=
\)$\(5.0600006\text{.}\) Estimate $\(5.06\text{.}\)</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-268" id=3D"so=
lution-268" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-268" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1976">When \(q=3D100\) and \(h=3D1\text{,}\) we compute</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\frac{C(100+1) - C(100)}{1} =3D 5.06060\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1977">When \(h=3D0.1\text{,}\) we compute</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\frac{C(100+0.1) - C(100)}{0.1} =3D 5.06006\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1978">Next, when \(h=3D0.001\text{,}\) we have</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\frac{C(100+0.001)-C(100)}{0.001} =3D 5.060006\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1979">Finally, when \(h=3D0.0001\text{,}\) we have</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\frac{C(100+0.0001)-C(100)}{0.0001} =3D 5.0600006\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1980">Therefore, we estimate that the instantaneous rate of chan=
ge when \(q=3D100\) is \(5.06\text{.}\)</p>
</div></div></article></div>
<article class=3D"exercise-like" id=3D"exercise-169"><a data-knowl=3D"" cla=
ss=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-exercise-169" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/mat=
h-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><=
h6 class=3D"heading">
<span class=3D"type">Exercise</span> <span class=3D"codenumber">4.2.12</spa=
n>.</h6></a></article><div id=3D"hk-exercise-169" class=3D"hidden-content t=
ex2jax_ignore"><article class=3D"exercise-like"><p id=3D"p-1981">The gross =
domestic product (GDP) of a certain country over 8 years is approximated by=
</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
G(t)=3D-0.2t^{3}+2.4t^{2}+60 \ \ \ (0 \leq t \leq 8)\text{,}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1981-part2">billions of dollars, where \(t=3D0\) corresponds to =
\(1992\text{.}\) The derivative of \(G(t)\) is given by</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
G'(t)=3D-0.6t^{2}+4.8t
\end{equation*}
</div>
<ol class=3D"lower-alpha">
<li id=3D"li-616">
<p id=3D"p-1982">Compute \(G'(0)\text{,}\)\(G'(1)\text{,...,}\)\(G'(8)\text=
{.}\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-336" id=3D"answ=
er-336" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-336" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(0\text{;}\)\(4.2\text{;}\)\(7.2\text{;}\)\(9\text{;}\)\(9.=
6\text{;}\)\(9\text{;}\)\(7.2\text{;}\)\(4.2\text{;}\)\(0\)</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-269" id=3D"so=
lution-269" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-269" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1983">We are given that \(G'(t)=3D-0.6t^2+4.8t\text{.}\) Therefo=
re, we compute:</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
G'(0) =3D -0.6(0)+4.8(0) =3D 0
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
G'(1) =3D -0.6+4.8 =3D 4.2
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
G'(2) =3D -0.6(4)+4.8(2) =3D 7.2
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
G'(3) =3D -0.6(9) + 4.8(3) =3D 9
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
G'(4) =3D -0.6(16)-4.8(4) =3D 9.6
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
G'(5) =3D -0.6(25)+4.8(5) =3D 9
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
G'(6) =3D -0.6(36)+4.8(6) =3D 7.2
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
G'(7) =3D -0.6(49)+4.8(7) =3D 4.2
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
G'(8) =3D -0.6(64)+4.8(8) =3D 0
\end{equation*}
</div>
</div></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-617">
<p id=3D"p-1984">Compute \(G''(0)\text{,}\)\(G''(1)\text{,...,}\)\(G''(8)\t=
ext{.}\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-337" id=3D"answ=
er-337" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-337" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(4.8\text{;}\)\(3.6\text{;}\)\(2.4\text{;}\)\(1.2\text{;}\)=
\(0\text{;}\)\(-1.2\text{;}\)\(-2.4\text{;}\)\(-3.6\text{;}\)\(-4.8\)</div>=
</div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-270" id=3D"so=
lution-270" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-270" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1985">We first compute the derivative of \(G'(t)\text{:}\)</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split} G''(t) \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{G'(t+h)-G'(t)}{h}\\ \amp =
=3D\lim_{h\to 0} \frac{(-0.6(t+h)^2+4.8(t+h)) - (-0.6t^2+4.8t)}{h}\\ \amp =
=3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{-0.6(t^2+2th+h^2) +4.8t + 4.8 h -0.6t^2 - 4.8 t }{h=
}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{-1.2th-0.6h^2+4.8h}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\=
to 0} (-1.2t -0.6h + 4.8)\\ \amp =3D -1.2t +4.8 \end{split}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1985-part2">Now compute:</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
G''(0) =3D -1.2(0) + 4.8 =3D 4.8
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
G''(1) =3D -1.2(1) + 4.8 =3D 3.6
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
G''(2) =3D -1.2(2)+4.8 =3D 2.4
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
G''(3) =3D -1.2(3)+4.8 =3D 1.2
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
G''(4) =3D -1.2(4)+4.8 =3D 0
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
G''(5) =3D -1.2(5)+4.8 =3D -1.2
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
G''(6) =3D -1.2(6)+4.8 =3D -2.4
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
G''(7) =3D -1.2(7) + 4.8 =3D -3.6
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
G''(8) =3D -1.2(8) + 4.8 =3D -4.8
\end{equation*}
</div>
</div></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-618">
<p id=3D"p-1986">What can you deduce from your results?</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-338" id=3D"answ=
er-338" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-338" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">We conclude that after a spectacular growth rate in the earl=
y years, the growth of the GDP cooled off. This cool off starts to occur ar=
ound year 5.</div></div>
</li>
</ol></article></div>
<article class=3D"exercise-like" id=3D"exercise-170"><a data-knowl=3D"" cla=
ss=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-exercise-170" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/mat=
h-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><=
h6 class=3D"heading">
<span class=3D"type">Exercise</span> <span class=3D"codenumber">4.2.13</spa=
n>.</h6></a></article><div id=3D"hk-exercise-170" class=3D"hidden-content t=
ex2jax_ignore"><article class=3D"exercise-like"><p id=3D"p-1987">It is esti=
mated that the number \(N(t)\) of individuals infected with a certain conta=
gious disease is</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
N(t)=3D-0.1t^{3}+1.5t^{2}+100 \ \ \ (0 \leq t \leq 7)
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1987-part2">where \(t\) is in months and \(t=3D0\) corresponds t=
o the initial outbreak. The derivative of \(N(t)\) is given by</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
N'(t)=3D-0.3t^{2}+3t\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1988">After 4 months, a drug which reduces the infectiousness of=
 the disease is developped.</p>
<ol class=3D"lower-alpha">
<li id=3D"li-619">
<p id=3D"p-1989">Verify that the number of infected individuals was increas=
ing for 7 months. (Hint: Compute \(N'(0)\text{,}\)\(N'(1)\text{,...,}\)\(N'=
(7)\)).</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-339" id=3D"answ=
er-339" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-339" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">0;2.7;4.8;6.3;7.2;7.5;7.2;6.3</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-271" id=3D"so=
lution-271" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-271" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1990">We are given that \(N'(t) =3D -0.3t^2+3t\text{.}\) Therefo=
re, we compute:</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
N'(0) =3D -0.3(0) + 3(0) =3D 0
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
N'(1) =3D -0.3(1) + 3(1) =3D 2.7
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
N'(2) =3D -0.3(2) + 3(2) =3D4.8
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
N'(3) =3D -0.3(3) + 3(3) =3D6.3
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
N'(4) =3D -0.3(4) + 3(4) =3D 7.2
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
N'(5) =3D -0.3(5) + 3(5) =3D 7.5
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
N'(6) =3D -0.3(6) + 3(6) =3D 7.2
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
N'(7) =3D -0.3(7) + 3(7) =3D 6.3
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1990-part2">Since \(N'(t) &gt; 0\) for all \(t\in (0,7]\text{,}\=
) the number of infected individuals was increasing during this time.</p>
</div></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-620">
<p id=3D"p-1991">Show that the drug was working by computing \(N''(4)\text{=
,}\)\(N''(5)\text{,}\)\(N''(6)\) and \(N''(7)\text{.}\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-340" id=3D"answ=
er-340" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-340" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">0.6;0;-0.6;-1.2</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-272" id=3D"so=
lution-272" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-272" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1992">In order to show the drug which was developped was working=
, we need to show that the rate at which the number of infected individuals=
 was increasing starts to decrease after \(t=3D4\) months. To do so, we fir=
st compute the second derivative:</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split} N''(t) \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{N(t+h)-N(t)}{h}\\ \amp =
=3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{\left(-0.3(t+h)^2 +3(t+h)\right) - \left(0.3t^2 + 3=
t\right)}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{-0.3(t^2+2th+h^2) + 3t + 3h - 0=
.2t^2 - 3t}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{-0.6th-0.3h^2+3h}{h}\\ \amp =
=3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{h(-0.6t-0.3h+3)}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} (-0.6t=
-0.3h+3)\\ \amp =3D -0.6t + 3 \end{split}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1992-part2">We now compute:</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
N''(4) =3D -0.6(4) + 3 =3D 0.6
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
N''(5) =3D -0.6(5) + 3 =3D 0
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
N''(6) =3D -0.6(6)+3 =3D -0.6
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
N''(7) =3D -0.6(7)+3 =3D -1.2
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1992-part3">This means that after 6 months=E2=80=942 months afte=
r the introduction of the drug=E2=80=94the rate at which number of infected=
 individuals was increasing starts to decrease. This indicates that the dru=
g had started to work.</p>
</div></div>
</li>
</ol></article></div>
<article class=3D"exercise-like" id=3D"exercise-171"><a data-knowl=3D"" cla=
ss=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-exercise-171" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/mat=
h-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><=
h6 class=3D"heading">
<span class=3D"type">Exercise</span> <span class=3D"codenumber">4.2.14</spa=
n>.</h6></a></article><div id=3D"hk-exercise-171" class=3D"hidden-content t=
ex2jax_ignore"><article class=3D"exercise-like"><p id=3D"p-1993">A certain =
manufacturer determines that the amount of defective products coming out of=
 their new Ontario plant \(t\) days after it opened can be estimated by</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
A(t) =3D -0.00006t^{5} + 0.00468t^{4}-0.1316t^{3} + 1.915t^2 - 17.63t + 100
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1993-part2">percent of the total number of units produced. The f=
irst and second derivatives of \(A(t)\) are given:</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
A'(t) =3D -0.0003t^{4}+0.01872t^{3}-0.3948t^{2}+3.83t-17.63
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
A''(t)=3D-0.0012t^{3}+0.05616t^{2}-0.7896t+3.83\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1994">Compute \(A'(10)\) and \(A''(10)\) and interpret your resu=
lts.</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-273" id=3D"so=
lution-273" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-273" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1995">From the formulas given for \(A'(t)\) and \(A''(t)\text{,}=
\) we compute</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
A'(10) =3D -3.09, \text{ and }  A''(10) =3D 0.35\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1996">This means that 10 days after the plant had opened, the am=
ount of defective products was decreasing at a rate of approximately 3% per=
 day. From the second derivative, we see that the rate at which the amount =
of defective products was decreasing was increasing at the rate of 0.35% pe=
r day per day.</p>
</div></div></article></div>
<article class=3D"exercise-like" id=3D"exercise-172"><a data-knowl=3D"" cla=
ss=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-exercise-172" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/mat=
h-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><=
h6 class=3D"heading">
<span class=3D"type">Exercise</span> <span class=3D"codenumber">4.2.15</spa=
n>.</h6></a></article><div id=3D"hk-exercise-172" class=3D"hidden-content t=
ex2jax_ignore"><article class=3D"exercise-like"><p id=3D"p-1997">Between th=
e years \(1980\) and \(2001\text{,}\) it is estimated that the percentage o=
f young families who own their own home can be approximated by the function=
</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
P(t)=3D33.55(t+5)^{0.205} \ \ \ (0 \leq t \leq 21)
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1997-part2">where \(t\) is measured in years, with \(t=3D0\) cor=
responding to the beginning of \(1980\text{.}\) The second derivative of \(=
P(t)\) is given by</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
-5.46781 (t+5)^{-1.795}\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-1998">Compute \(P''(20)\) and interpret your results.</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-274" id=3D"so=
lution-274" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-274" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-1999">We are given that</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
P''(t) =3D -5.46781(t+5)^{-1.795}\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-2000">Therefore, when \(t=3D20\text{,}\) we have</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
P''(20) =3D -5.46781(25)^{-1.795}=3D -0.0169243\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-2001">This means that in the year 2000, The rate of change of yo=
ung families owning their own homes is decreasing at a rate of approximatel=
y 0.02%/yr\(^2\text{.}\)</p>
</div></div></article></div>
<article class=3D"exercise-like" id=3D"exercise-173"><a data-knowl=3D"" cla=
ss=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-exercise-173" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/mat=
h-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><=
h6 class=3D"heading">
<span class=3D"type">Exercise</span> <span class=3D"codenumber">4.2.16</spa=
n>.</h6></a></article><div id=3D"hk-exercise-173" class=3D"hidden-content t=
ex2jax_ignore"><article class=3D"exercise-like"><p id=3D"p-2002">A certain =
manufacturer estimates that the total weekly cost in producing \(q\) units =
is</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
C(q) =3D 2000+2q-0.0001q^{2} \ \ \ 0 \leq q \leq 6000\text{,}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-2002-part2">dollars.</p>
<ol class=3D"lower-alpha">
<li id=3D"li-621">
<p id=3D"p-2003">What is the actual cost incurred in producing the \(1001\)=
st and the \(2001\)st unit?</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-341" id=3D"answ=
er-341" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-341" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">$\(1.80\text{;}\) $\(1.60\text{.}\)</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-275" id=3D"so=
lution-275" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-275" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-2004">The actual cost incurred in producing the 1001st unit is</=
p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
C(1001)-C(1000) =3D 3901.8 - 3900 =3D 1.80
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-2004-part2">dollars. Similarly, the actual cost incurred in prod=
ucing the 2001st unit is</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
C(2001)-C(2000) =3D 5601.6 - 5600 =3D 1.60
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-2004-part3">dollars.</p>
</div></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-622">
<p id=3D"p-2005">What is the marginal cost when \(q=3D1000\) and \(2000\tex=
t{?}\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-342" id=3D"answ=
er-342" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-342" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">$\(1.80\text{;}\) $\(1.60\text{.}\)</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-276" id=3D"so=
lution-276" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-276" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-2006">We first compute the derivative:</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split} C'(q) \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{C(q+h)-C(q)}{h}\\ \amp =3D=
 \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{(2000+2(q+h)-0.0001(q+h)^2) - (2000 + 2q - 0.0001q^2)}=
{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{2h - 0.0002qh - 0.0001h^2}{h} \\ \amp =
=3D \lim_{h\to 0} (2-0.0002q-0.0001h)\\ \amp =3D 2-0.0002q \end{split}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-2006-part2">The marginal cost when \(q=3D1000\) is</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
C'(1000) =3D 2-0.0002(1000) =3D 1.80\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-2006-part3">The marginal cost when \(q=3D2000\) is</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
C'(2000) =3D 2-0.0002(2000) =3D 1.60\text{.}
\end{equation*}
</div>
</div></div>
</li>
</ol></article></div>
<article class=3D"exercise-like" id=3D"exercise-174"><a data-knowl=3D"" cla=
ss=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-exercise-174" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/mat=
h-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><=
h6 class=3D"heading">
<span class=3D"type">Exercise</span> <span class=3D"codenumber">4.2.17</spa=
n>.</h6></a></article><div id=3D"hk-exercise-174" class=3D"hidden-content t=
ex2jax_ignore"><article class=3D"exercise-like"><p id=3D"p-2007">A movie th=
eatre determines that their monthly revenue can be estimated by</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
R(q) =3D 8000q-100q^{2}
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-2007-part2">dollars when the price per movie ticket is \(q\) dol=
lars.</p>
<ol class=3D"lower-alpha">
<li id=3D"li-623">
<p id=3D"p-2008">Find the marginal revenue \(R'\text{.}\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-343" id=3D"answ=
er-343" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-343" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(8000-200q\)</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-277" id=3D"so=
lution-277" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-277" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-2009">We differentiate:</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
\begin{split} R'(q) \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{R(q+h)-R(q)}{h}\\ \amp =3D=
 \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{(8000(q+h)-100(q+h)^2) - (8000q - 100q^2)}{h}\\ \amp =
=3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{8000q + 8000h -100(q^2+2qh+h^2) - 8000q + 100q^2}{h=
}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{h\to 0} \frac{8000h - 200qh-100h^2}{h}\\ \amp =3D \lim_{=
h\to 0} (8000 - 200q - 100h)\\ \amp =3D 8000 - 200q \end{split}
\end{equation*}
</div>
</div></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-624">
<p id=3D"p-2010">Compute \(R'(39)\text{,}\) \(R'(40)\text{,}\) and \(R'(41)=
\text{.}\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-344" id=3D"answ=
er-344" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-344" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(200\text{,}\)\(0\text{,}\)\(-200\text{.}\)</div></div>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-278" id=3D"so=
lution-278" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-278" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">
<p id=3D"p-2011">We compute:</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
R'(39) =3D 8000-200(39) =3D 200
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
R'(40) =3D 8000-200(40)=3D 0
\end{equation*}
</div>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
R'(41) =3D 8000-200(41) =3D -200
\end{equation*}
</div>
</div></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-625">
<p id=3D"p-2012">Based on the results above, what price should the theatre =
charge in order to maximize their revenue?</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-345" id=3D"answ=
er-345" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-345" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">We conclude that the movie theatre should charge $40 per tic=
ket.</div></div>
</li>
</ol></article></div>
<article class=3D"exercise-like" id=3D"exercise-175"><a data-knowl=3D"" cla=
ss=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-exercise-175" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/mat=
h-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><=
h6 class=3D"heading">
<span class=3D"type">Exercise</span> <span class=3D"codenumber">4.2.18</spa=
n>.</h6></a></article><div id=3D"hk-exercise-175" class=3D"hidden-content t=
ex2jax_ignore"><article class=3D"exercise-like"><p id=3D"p-2013">The demand=
 function for a certain product is given by</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
p =3D -0.04q+800 \ \ \ 0\leq q \leq 20,000
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-2013-part2">where \(p\) denotes the unit price in dollars and \(=
q\) denotes the quantity demanded.</p>
<ol class=3D"lower-alpha">
<li id=3D"li-626">
<p id=3D"p-2014">Determine the revenue function \(R\text{.}\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-solution-279" id=3D"so=
lution-279" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course=
%20Notes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Solution</spa=
n></a><div id=3D"hk-solution-279" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><=
div class=3D"solution">\(R(q)=3D pq =3D (-0.04q + 800)q =3D -0.04q^{2}+800q=
\text{.}\)</div></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-627">
<p id=3D"p-2015">Determine the marginal revenue function \(R'\text{.}\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-346" id=3D"answ=
er-346" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-346" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">We can again use the result from 4.2.1(d) to find \(R'(q)=3D=
-0.08q+800\text{.}\)</div></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-628">
<p id=3D"p-2016">Compute \(R'(5000)\text{.}\) What can you deduce from your=
 results?</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-347" id=3D"answ=
er-347" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-347" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(R'(5000)=3D400\text{.}\) We see that, when the level of pr=
oduction is set at \(5000\) units, the production of the \(5001\)st unit wi=
ll bring an additional revenue of approximately $\(400\text{.}\)</div></div=
>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-629">
<p id=3D"p-2017">If the total cost in producing \(q\) units is given by</p>
<div class=3D"displaymath">
\begin{equation*}
C(q)=3D200q+300,000
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p id=3D"p-2017-part2">determine the profit function \(P(q)\text{.}\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-348" id=3D"answ=
er-348" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-348" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(P(q)=3D R(q) - C(q) =3D -0.04q^{2}+600q-300,000\text{.}\)<=
/div></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-630">
<p id=3D"p-2018">Find the marginal profit function \(P'\text{.}\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-349" id=3D"answ=
er-349" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-349" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(P'(q)=3D-2(0.04)q+600 =3D -0.08q + 600\text{.}\)</div></di=
v>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-631">
<p id=3D"p-2019">Compute \(P'(5000)\) and \(P'(8000)\text{.}\)</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-350" id=3D"answ=
er-350" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-350" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution">\(P'(5000)=3D200\text{,}\) \(P'(8000)=3D-40\)</div></div>
</li>
<li id=3D"li-632">
<p id=3D"p-2020">Sketch the graph of the profit function. What can you dedu=
ce from your results?</p>
<a data-knowl=3D"" class=3D"id-ref" data-refid=3D"hk-answer-351" id=3D"answ=
er-351" href=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20N=
otes/sec_TheDerivativeFunction.html"><span class=3D"type">Answer</span></a>=
<div id=3D"hk-answer-351" class=3D"hidden-content tex2jax_ignore"><div clas=
s=3D"solution"><p id=3D"p-2021">The profit increases as production increase=
s, peaking at \(7500\) units. Beyond this level, profit falls. \(P(q)\) sho=
wn in millions of dollars. </p><div class=3D"image-box" style=3D"width: 60%=
; margin-left: 20%; margin-right: 20%;"><img src=3D"https://www.sfu.ca/math=
-coursenotes/Math%20157%20Course%20Notes/images/image-225.svg" style=3D"wid=
th: 100%; height: auto;" alt=3D""></div><p id=3D"p-2021-part2"></p></div></=
div>
</li>
</ol></article></div></article></section></div></main>
</div>
